# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: components-of-jet-engines
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] An **abradable coating** is a coating made of an abradable material – meaning if it rubs against a more abrasive material in motion, the former will be worn whereas the latter will face no wear.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] Abradable coatings provide a .1 to .2% performance improvement compared to those without coating.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] Abradable coatings are used in aircraft jet engines in the compressor and turbine sections where a minimal clearance is needed between the blade tips and the casing.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] Abradable coatings have been in use by aero-engine manufacturers in some form or fashion for roughly 50 years.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] Abradable powder coatings provide an economical and environmentally friendly way to improve the efficiency of engines, compressors and pumps by fine-tuning the operational fit of internal components such as pistons, rotors and cases.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] In typical turbo machinery, the clearance between blade tips and the casing must account for thermal and inertial expansion as well as changes in concentricity due to shock loading events.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] To prevent catastrophic tip to casing contact, conservatively large clearances must be employed.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] In small turboprop aircraft, the angle at which abradable coating is applied is impacted by the necessity of the coating process performed at spray angles less than 60 degrees.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/abradable-coating] The role of abradable coatings is not only to allow for closer clearances, but to automatically adjust clearances, in-situ, to accept physical events and/or thermal scenarios that may be found in a devices operational history.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] A **variable cycle engine** (**VCE**), also referred to as **adaptive cycle engine** (**ACE**), is an aircraft jet engine that is designed to operate efficiently under mixed flight conditions, such as subsonic, transonic and supersonic.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] An **advanced technology engine** is a turbine engine that allows different turbines to spin at different, individually optimum speeds, instead of at one speed for all.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] It emerged on larger airplanes, before finding other applications.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The next generation of supersonic transport (SST) may require some form of VCE.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] To reduce aircraft drag at supercruise, SST engines require a high specific thrust (net thrust/airflow) to minimize the powerplant's cross-sectional area.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] This implies a high jet velocity during supersonic cruise and at take-off, which makes the aircraft noisy.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] So for zero flight velocity, specific thrust is directly proportional to jet velocity.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The Rolls-Royce/Snecma Olympus 593 in Concorde had a high specific thrust in supersonic cruise and at dry take-off.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The problem was compounded by the need for a modest amount of afterburning (reheat) at take-off (and transonic acceleration).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] One SST VCE concept is the tandem fan engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The engine has two fans, both mounted on the low-pressure shaft, separated by a significant axial gap.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The engine operates in series mode while cruising and parallel mode while take-off, climb-out, approach, and final-descent.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In series mode, air enters in the front of the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] After passing through the front fan, the air passes directly into the second fan, so that the engine behaves much like a turbofan.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In parallel mode, air leaving the front fan exits the engine through an auxiliary nozzle on the underside of the nacelle, skipping the rear fan.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Intakes on each side of the engine open to capture air and send it directly to the rear fan and the rest of the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Parallel mode substantially increases the total air accelerated by the engine, lowering the velocity of the air and accompanying noise.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In the 1970s, Boeing modified a Pratt & Whitney JT8D to use a tandem fan configuration and successfully demonstrated the switch from series to parallel operation (and vice versa) with the engine running, albeit at partial power.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In the mid-tandem fan concept, a high specific flow single stage fan is located between the high pressure (HP) and low pressure (LP) compressors of a turbojet core.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The LP compressor exit flow passes through passages within the fan disc, directly underneath the fan blades.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Some bypass air enters the engine via an auxiliary intake.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] During take-off and approach the engine behaves much like a conventional turbofan, with an acceptable jet noise level (i.e., low specific thrust).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] However, for supersonic cruise, the fan variable inlet guide vanes and auxiliary intake close to minimize bypass flow and increase specific thrust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In this mode the engine acts more like a 'leaky' turbojet (e.g. the F404).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In the mixed-flow turbofan with ejector concept, a low bypass ratio engine is mounted in front of a long tube, called an ejector.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] It is deployed during take-off and approach.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Turbofan exhaust gases send air into the ejector via an auxiliary air intake, thereby reducing the specific thrust/mean jet velocity of the final exhaust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The mixed-flow design is not particularly efficient at low speed, but is considerably simpler.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The three-stream architecture adds a third, directable air stream.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] This stream bypasses the core when fuel efficiency is required or through the core for greater power.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Examples include the General Electric XA100 and the Pratt & Whitney XA101, as well as the propulsion system for the Next Generation Air Dominance (NGAD) fighter.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] General Electric developed a variable cycle engine, known as the GE37 or General Electric YF120, for the YF-22/YF-23 fighter aircraft competition, in the late 1980s.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] GE used a double bypass/hybrid fan arrangement, but never disclosed how they exploited the concept.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The Air Force instead selected the conventional Pratt & Whitney F119 for what became the Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Geared turbofans are also used in the following engines, some still in development: Garrett TFE731, Lycoming ALF 502/LF 507, Pratt & Whitney PW1000G, Turbomeca Astafan, and Turbomeca Aspin, and Aviadvigatel PD-18R.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The Rolls Royce Ultrafan is the largest and most efficient engine to allow multiple turbine speeds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Startup Astro Mechanica is developing what it calls a turboelectric-adaptive jet engine that shifts from turbofan to turbojet to ramjet mode as it accelerates from a standing start to a projected Mach 6.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] This is achieved by using a dual turbine approach.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The second turbine acts as the propulsion unit.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The turbogenerator powers an electric motor that controls the compressor of the second turbine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The motor can change speeds to keep the fan turning at the ideal RPM for a specific flight mode.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In turbojet and ramjet modes, the inlet is narrowed to compress the air and eliminate bypass.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The turbogenerator is commercially available, while the propulsion unit is built by the company.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] A key innovation is that electric motors have dramatically increased their power density so that the weight of the motor is no longer prohibitive.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Instead of a fixed gearbox, it uses an electric motor to turn the turbine(s) behind the fan at an ideal speed for each phase of flight.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The company claimed it would support efficient take-off, subsonic, supersonic, and hypersonic speeds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The electric motor is powered by a generator in turn powered by a turbine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The approach relies on the improved power density of novel electric motors such as yokeless dual-rotor axial flux motors that offer far more kw/kg than conventional designs that were too heavy for such an application.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] Air flows in through a turbogenerator to produce electric power to power an electric motor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] The electric motor adaptively controls the propulsion unit, allowing it to behave like a turbofan, turbojet, or ramjet depending on airspeed.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] In effect the engine can operate at any point along the specific impulse (Isp) curve - high Isp at low speed or low Isp at high speed.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/advanced-technology-engine] It is in some respects similar to turbo-electric marine engines that allow propellers to turn at a different speed than the steam turbines that power them.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] An **air-start system** is a power source used to provide the initial rotation to start large diesel engines and gas turbines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Compared to a gasoline (petrol) engine, a diesel engine has a very high compression ratio, an essential design feature, as it is the heat of compression that ignites the fuel.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] An electric starter with sufficient power to turn a large diesel engine would itself be so large as to be impractical so there is a need for an alternative system.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] An air start system has three main components along with various safety components, namely the air start injector, the distributor and the air receivers.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] When the system is initiated, starting air from the receivers is distributed by the distributor unit to each respective air start valve according to the firing order of the engine’s cylinders.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Safety components include flame traps, to prevent air line explosions, a turning gear interlock which ensures that air-start cannot be initiated when the turning gear is engaged, relief valves and isolation valves, as well as drain valves at certain points along the system.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Control components include the control valves and remote air-start valves.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] A direct start system as used on a marine slow-speed diesel is required to have up to 12 starts on a non-reversing engine or 6 starts on a reversible, or geared, engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] When starting the engine, compressed air is admitted to whichever cylinder has a piston just over top dead center, forcing it downward.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] As the engine starts to turn, the air-start valve on the next cylinder in line opens to continue the rotation.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] After several rotations, fuel is injected into the cylinders, the engine starts running and the air is cut off.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] To further complicate matters, a large engine is usually "blown over" first with zero fuel settings and the indicator cocks open, to prove that the engine is clear of any water build up and that everything is free to turn.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] After a successful blow ahead and a blow astern, the indicator cocks are closed on all the cylinders, and then the engine can be started on fuel.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Significant complexity is added to the engine by using an air-start system, as the cylinder head must have an extra valve in each cylinder to admit the air in for starting, plus the required control systems.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] This added complexity and cost limits the use of air-starters to very large and expensive reciprocating engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Another method of air-starting an internal combustion engine is by using compressed air or gas to drive a fluid motor in place of an electric motor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] They can be used to start engines from 5 to 320 liters in size and if more starting power is necessary two or more motors can be used.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Starters of this type are used in place of electric motors because of their lighter weight and higher reliability.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] They can also outlast an electric starter by a factor of three and are easier to rebuild.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Engines operating in underground mining activities tend to operate on this type of starter system to reduce the risk of an electrical system igniting flammable material.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] All vane type air starters should have a lubricator installed to insure long-life and maximum performance.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Lubricators give the moving parts a needed friction barrier, reduce metal corrosion and keep vanes sealed properly against the cylinder walls.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Even the so-called lube-free air starters require lubrication to prolong trouble free life.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Two basic lubricator devices are typically employed.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] One is an in-line or reservoir type that typically stores up to 2 quarts of lubricant, and is installed along the air supply line.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] The second style of lubricator is a small one shot device that dispenses a measured amount of lubricant every time the starter is engaged.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Installed directly onto the air inlet of the starter, the in-line lubricators are self priming pneumatic pumps that require a 1/4″ lubrication line piped from as far away as 4 feet.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Air Starter lubricators perform best using misting type, non-detergent oils such as diesel fuel or Marvel Mystery oil.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] If emissions are a concern, there are environmentally friendly type lubricants available on the market.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Not all air starters require lubrication.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Turbine type air starters do not require air motor lubrication, although some turbine air starters do use an oil filled transmission that may require periodic inspections and maintenance.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Compressed air has been used to start gas turbine engines using air impingement starting (in which air is directed at the engine turbine blades through nozzles in the turbine casing, used on US Navy General Electric J79 engines).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] It is much more efficient to use an air turbine starter (ATS) which is usually mounted on an accessory gearbox.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] An early axial compressor turbojet had an ATS located in the compressor nose cone (eg particular variants of the J79).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Air impingement starting was not used for US military aircraft after the F-4B, A-5A and F-5 as the pneumatic energy requirement was several times greater than when using an air turbine starter.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] The gas turbine compressor required to start a J79 with impingement starting was sufficient to start two J79 engines simultaneously in a B-58 when using air turbine starters.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] An ATS has its own turbine and gears to change its low torque and high speed to low speed and high torque at the engine mounting pad.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Further gears in the engine gearbox connect to the engine shaft (high pressure spool on multi-spool engines).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] Compared with electric starters, air-starters have a higher power-to-weight ratio so are used on large engines as an electric starter would be too big and, with its cables, too heavy and expensive.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] However, for smaller engines, which don't need as much starter power, an electric starter is more suitable.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-start-system] It has a dual function as a generator (is known as a starter/generator) at speeds above which the engine no longer requires starter assistance.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] There are many different types of air turborockets.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and many others.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The benefit of this setup is increased specific impulse over that of a rocket.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] For the same carried mass of propellant as a rocket motor, the overall output of the air turborocket is much higher.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] In addition, it provides thrust throughout a much wider speed range than a ramjet, yet is much cheaper and easier to control than a gas turbine engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The air turborocket fills a niche (in terms of cost, reliability, ruggedness, and duration of thrust) between the solid-fuel rocket motor and gas turbine engine for missile applications.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] A **turborocket** is a type of aircraft engine combining elements of a jet engine and a rocket.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] It typically comprises a multi-stage fan driven by a turbine, which is driven by the hot gases exhausting from a series of small rocket-like motors mounted around the turbine inlet.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust gases mix with the fan discharge air, and combust with the air from the compressor before exhausting through a convergent-divergent propelling nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Once a jet engine goes high enough in an atmosphere, there is insufficient oxygen to burn the jet fuel.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The idea behind a turborocket is to supplement the atmospheric oxygen with an onboard supply.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] This allows operation at a much higher altitude than a normal engine would allow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turborocket design offers a mixture of benefits with drawbacks.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] It is not a true rocket, so it cannot operate in space.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Cooling the engine is not a problem because the burner and its hot exhaust gases are located behind the turbine blades.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The air turboramjet engine is a combined cycle engine that merges aspects of turbojet and ramjet engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turboramjet is a hybrid engine that essentially consists of a turbojet mounted inside a ramjet.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turbojet core is mounted inside a duct that contains a combustion chamber downstream of the turbojet nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turboramjet can be run in turbojet mode at takeoff and during low-speed flight but then switch to ramjet mode to accelerate to high Mach numbers.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The operation of the engine is controlled using bypass flaps located just downstream of the diffuser.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] During low-speed flight, controllable flaps close the bypass duct and force air directly into the compressor section of the turbojet.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] During high-speed flight, the flaps block the flow into the turbojet, and the engine operates like a ramjet using the *aft* combustion chamber to produce thrust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The engine would start out operating as a turbojet during takeoff and while climbing to altitude.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Upon reaching high subsonic speed, the portion of the engine downstream of the turbojet would be used as an afterburner to accelerate the plane above the speed of sound.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] At lower speeds, air passes through an inlet and is then compressed by an axial compressor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] That compressor is driven by a turbine, which is powered by hot, high-pressure gas from a combustion chamber.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] These initial aspects are very similar to how a turbojet operates, however, there are several differences.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The first is that the combustor in the turboramjet is often separate from the main airflow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Instead of combining air from the compressor with fuel to combust, the turboramjet combustor may use hydrogen and oxygen, carried on the aircraft, as its fuel for the combustor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The air compressed by the compressor bypasses the combustor and turbine section of the engine, where it is mixed with the turbine exhaust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turbine exhaust can be designed to be fuel-rich (i.e., the combustor does not burn all the fuel) which, when mixed with the compressed air, creates a hot fuel-air mixture which is ready to burn again.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] More fuel is injected into this air where it is again combusted.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The exhaust is ejected through a propelling nozzle, generating thrust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Picture shown lacks required bypass ducting around the compressor for ramjet operation.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Shown is a low bypass turbojet with re-heat.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] The turboramjet engine is used when space is constrained, as it takes up less space than separate ramjet and turbojet engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] Since a ramjet must already be traveling at high speeds before it will start working, a ramjet-powered aircraft is incapable of taking off from a runway under its own power; that is the advantage of the turbojet, which is a member of the gas turbine family of engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] A turbojet does not rely purely on the motion of the engine to compress the incoming air flow; instead, the turbojet contains some additional rotating machinery that compresses incoming air and allows the engine to function during takeoff and at slow speeds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] In applications which stay relatively in the atmosphere and require longer durations of lower thrust over a specific speed range the air turborocket can have a weight advantage over the standard solid fuel rocket motor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/air-turborocket] In terms of volumetric requirements, the rocket motor has the advantage due to the lack of inlet ducts and other air management devices.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] An **aircraft engine**, often referred to as an **aero engine**, is the power component of an aircraft propulsion system.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Aircraft using power components are referred to as **powered flight**.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Most aircraft engines are either piston engines or gas turbines, although a few have been rocket powered and in recent years many small UAVs have used electric motors.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The market for aircraft engines, especially jet engines, has very high barriers to entry.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Aircraft engines use highly advanced technology and materials, take around eight years and billions of dollars or euros to develop, and must pass exacting safety certifications by aviation safety authorities.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Consequently, entering the engine market is extremely capital- and time-intensive, which helps protect existing manufacturers from competition.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The last successful entry in the global market for jet engines was General Electric in the 1970s.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] These barriers to entry make the market very lucrative for existing manufacturers.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] As of 2025, the leading jet engine manufacturers reported shareholder returns from between 100 and 1,000 percent over the last five years, compared to small or negative returns for their principal clients, Airbus and Boeing.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The engines themselves are typically sold at a loss, but manufacturers derive their profits from the sale of maintenance services and spare parts over the roughly thirty-year lifespan of an engine, following the razor and blades business model.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] This creates a perverse incentive for manufacturers to slow the production or delay the delivery of new engines, because they profit most from the use of old engines, which need more service and spare parts than new ones.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] This contributed to the unavailability of new engines, creating a bottleneck for Airbus and Boeing's efforts to increase aircraft production in the post-COVID resurgence of aviation after 2023.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] A radial engine has the cylinders placed in a circle around the crankshaft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The engine is air-cooled, which can be a problem since they may overheat.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Compared to liquid-cooled engines, radial engines have the advantage of being more rugged and capable of absorbing damage.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Rotating radial engines have the cylinders in a circle around the crankcase, as in a radial engine, (see above), but the crankshaft is fixed to the airframe and the propeller is fixed to the engine case, so that the crankcase and cylinders rotate.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The advantage of this arrangement is that a satisfactory flow of cooling air is maintained even at low airspeeds, retaining the weight advantage and simplicity of a conventional air-cooled engine without one of their major drawbacks.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The first practical rotary engine was the Gnome Omega designed by the Seguin brothers and first flown in 1909.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Its relative reliability and good power to weight ratio changed aviation dramatically.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine is about one half the weight and size of a traditional four-stroke cycle piston engine of equal power output, and much lower in complexity.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] In an aircraft application, the power-to-weight ratio is very important, making the Wankel engine a good choice.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Because the engine is typically constructed with an aluminium housing and a steel rotor, and aluminium expands more than steel when heated, a Wankel engine does not seize when overheated, unlike a piston engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] This is an important safety factor for aeronautical use.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Considerable development of these designs started after World War II, but at the time the aircraft industry favored the use of turbine engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] It was believed that turbojet or turboprop engines could power all aircraft, from the largest to smallest designs.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The Wankel engine did not find many applications in aircraft, but was used by Mazda in a popular line of sports cars.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The French company Citroën had developed Wankel powered RE-2 helicopter in 1970's.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] In modern times the Wankel engine has been used in motor gliders where the compactness, light weight, and smoothness are crucially important.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Starting in the 1930s, attempts were made to produce a practical aircraft diesel engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] In general, Diesel engines are more reliable and much better suited to running for long periods of time at medium power settings.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Improvements in Diesel technology in automobiles (leading to much better power-weight ratios), the Diesel's much better fuel efficiency, and the high relative taxation of AVGAS compared to Jet A1 in Europe have all seen a revival of interest in the use of diesels for aircraft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Thielert Aircraft Engines converted Mercedes Diesel automotive engines, certified them for aircraft use, and became an OEM provider to Diamond Aviation for their light twin.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Financial problems have plagued Thielert, so Diamond's affiliate — Austro Engine — developed the new AE300 turbodiesel, also based on a Mercedes engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] A turboprop consists of an intake, reduction gearbox, compressor, combustor, turbine, and a propelling nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Air enters the intake and is compressed by the compressor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Jet fuel is then added to the compressed air in the combustor, where it then combusts.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The hot combustion gases expand through the turbine stages, generating power at the point of exhaust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Some of the power generated by the turbine is used to drive the compressor and electric generator.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The gases are then exhausted from the turbine, but do not provide enough power to create a major portion of the total thrust, since almost all of the engine's power is used to drive the propeller.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] A **turboshaft** engine is a form of gas turbine that is optimized to produce shaft horsepower rather than jet thrust.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The engine has two major parts assemblies: the 'gas generator' and the 'power section'.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The gas generator consists of the compressor, combustion chambers with ignitors and fuel nozzles, and one or more stages of turbine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The power section consists of additional stages of turbines, a gear reduction system, and the shaft output.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The gas generator creates the hot expanding gases to drive the power section; the engine accessories may be driven either by the gas generator or by the power section.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] A number of electrically powered aircraft, such as the QinetiQ Zephyr, have been designed since the 1960s.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] In France in late 2007, a conventional light aircraft powered by an 18 kW electric motor using lithium polymer batteries was flown, covering more than 50 kilometers (31 mi), the first electric airplane to receive a certificate of airworthiness.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] On 18 May 2020, the Pipistrel E-811 was the first electric aircraft engine to be awarded a type certificate by EASA for use in general aviation.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The E-811 powers the Pipistrel Velis Electro.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Many big companies, such as Siemens, are developing high-performance electric engines for aircraft use; also, SAE shows new developments in elements as pure Copper core electric motors with a better efficiency.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] A hybrid system as emergency back-up and for added power in take-off is offered for sale by Axter Aerospace, Madrid, Spain.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The term *advanced technology engine* refers to the modern generation of jet engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] A rocket turbine engine is a combination of two types of propulsion engines: a liquid-propellant rocket and a turbine jet engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Its power-to-weight ratio is a little higher than a regular jet engine, and it works at higher altitudes.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] At the April 2018 ILA Berlin Air Show, Munich-based research institute de:Bauhaus Luftfahrt presented a high-efficiency composite cycle engine for 2050, combining a geared turbofan with a piston engine core.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The 11,200 lb (49.7 kN) engine could power a 50-seat regional jet.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Its cruise TSFC would be 11.5 g/kN/s (0.406 lb/lbf/hr) for an overall engine efficiency of 48.2%, for a burner temperature of 1,700 K (1,430 °C), an overall pressure ratio of 38 and a peak pressure of 30 MPa (300 bar).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Although engine weight increases by 30%, aircraft fuel consumption is reduced by 15%.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Sponsored by the European Commission under Framework 7 project LEMCOTEC, Bauhaus Luftfahrt, MTU Aero Engines and GKN Aerospace presented the concept in 2015, raising the overall engine pressure ratio to over 100 for a 15.2% fuel burn reduction compared to 2025 engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] On multi-engine aircraft, engine positions are numbered from left to right from the point of view of the pilot looking forward, so for example on a four-engine aircraft such as the Boeing 747, engine No.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] 1 is on the left side, farthest from the fuselage, while engine No.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] 3 is on the right side nearest to the fuselage.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] In the case of the twin-engine English Electric Lightning, which has two fuselage-mounted jet engines one above the other, engine No.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] 1 is below and to the front of engine No.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Refineries blend Avgas with tetraethyllead (TEL) to achieve these high octane ratings, a practice that governments no longer permit for gasoline intended for road vehicles.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] The shrinking supply of TEL and the possibility of environmental legislation banning its use have made a search for replacement fuels for general aviation aircraft a priority for pilots’ organizations.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Model aircraft typically use nitro engines (also known as "glow engines" due to the use of a glow plug) powered by glow fuel, a mixture of methanol, nitromethane, and lubricant.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Electrically powered model airplanes and helicopters are also commercially available.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/aircraft-engine] Small multicopter UAVs are almost always powered by electricity, but larger gasoline-powered designs are under development.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This article describes the components and systems found in jet engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It uses two example engines; the type most familiar to the general public, the modern airliner engine, and the military afterburning engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The components and systems make up what is known as a bare engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The article also has a section on inlets.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Although the inlet is not part of the engine, the engine relies on it to help prevent compressor surging (by reducing inlet distortion), and to give a pressure boost to the engine which reduces its fuel consumption (by converting the relative speed of the approaching air into pressure).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The article also mentions the nacelle because the outside of an airliner engine has to be streamlined so that as little of its thrust as possible is lost to the drag of the air flowing past the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Engines for airliners are enclosed in a streamlined pod called a nacelle which hangs under the wing or, on smaller aircraft, on the side of the aircraft behind the wing.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The most fundamental part of the engine is the gas generator ( also known as the core) because every gas turbine engine needs one (it has 3 parts, compressor, combustion chamber and turbine).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Early jet engines (turbojets) were just a gas generator until additional parts were added to reduce fuel consumption.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] In front was added a fan and, at the back, another turbine, both connected together by a shaft going through the middle of the gas generator, (and known as a fanjet, bypass engine, or turbofan).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For an airline passenger the gas generator is out-of-sight in the middle of the engine and all that can be seen of the engine itself are the fan at the front and the turbine for the fan at the back inside the core nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The major components of an airliner engine are shown on the 'Schematic of a high bypass turbofan'.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] **Spool** is a name given to a complete rotor consisting of compressor, turbine and connecting shaft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Two significant extra components are also used on modern airliner engines compared to the 2-spool arrangement shown above.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Most of the same components are needed but some differ noticeably in appearance, as does the bare engine itself.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The fan is much smaller and has more than one set of blades, for example.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] There is no thrust reverser but there is an afterburner.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] One or two engines are installed in the body of the aircraft behind the cockpit.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The job of the compressor is to raise the pressure of ambient air as high as possible with the level of technology existing at the time (the higher the pressure the greater the proportion of energy in the fuel that is transferred to the air in the combustor, which means less wasted fuel).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For the illustrated J79 engine it was 12 atmospheres (General Electric compressor knowledge in 1952).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The air is squeezed by very fast moving blades in a close-fitting tube.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The exit from the tube is smaller than the entry as the squeezed air (higher density/smaller volume) takes up less space.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The high pressure is attained at high speed and the small exit area is only correct for the high-speed density (small volume).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] At low engine speeds the slower moving blades don't compress the air so much and the exit area is too small to pass the low-speed (bigger) volume.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This affects the angle the blades meet their approaching air (see following explanation).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The speed of the air moving through the compressor and the speed of the blades combine to give the blade angle of attack (explained using velocity triangles) and if too much, similar to an aircraft wing, the compressor air flow stalls.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This condition happens at low compressor speeds and stops the compressor getting to its high-speed/works-well condition.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Three additions to a compressor enable it to run without blade stall at low speeds (see following).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The J79 illustration shows the use of variable angle blades in the first half of the compressor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The J57 illustration shows a (combined 12 atmosphere) compressor split into two separately-spinning compressors, both of which work well because, individually, they only compress their own bit of airflow 3 or 4 times (3x4=12).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The Avon illustration shows where air escapes at low engine speeds (three bleed valves).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] These examples are all early jet engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The volume of air determines the amount of work which has to be put into compressing or which can be got out during expansion.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] So more work can be obtained after heating compressed air (due to the increased volume of the working fluid) by expanding it (in a turbine) than was needed to compress it.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The combustor heats the air and with the turbine driving the compressor there is a surplus available to form a propelling jet (or drive an additional turbine).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Slowing the air reduces the pressure loss in the combustor (less pressure loss, lower fuel consumption).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Also, less pressure loss means combustion takes place at a higher pressure which increases combustion efficiency (lower fuel consumption).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The air leaving the compressor is initially slowed when it enters a bigger annulus (see accompanying image of Adour engine).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Air going into the combustor with the fuel spray is still going too fast for a flame to exist.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The flame front doesn't move fast enough to remain inside the combustor against the incoming air flow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A sheltered combustion zone with a reverse flow region has to be established (using air swirl around the fuel spray and holes in the combustor wall).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This enables the flame to remain in a stable location (primary zone) near the fuel nozzles and is a continuous ignition source for incoming air and fuel.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] After the air required for combustion has entered the front of the combustor further air enters through many holes in the wall of the combustor to provide wall-cooling with a film of cooler air to insulate the metal surfaces which have a protective thermal barrier.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Because a turbine expands from high to low pressure, there is no such thing as turbine surge or stall.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The turbine needs fewer stages than the compressor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The blades have more curvature and the gas stream velocities are higher.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Designers must, however, prevent the turbine blades and vanes from melting in a very high temperature and stress environment.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Consequently, bleed air extracted from the compression system is often used to cool the turbine blades/vanes internally.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Other solutions are improved materials and/or special insulating coatings.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The discs must be specially shaped to withstand the high stresses imposed by the rotating blades.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Improved materials help to keep disc weight down.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] All jet engines require high temperature gas for good efficiency, typically achieved by combusting hydrocarbon or hydrogen fuel.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Combustion temperatures can be as high as 3500K (5841F) in rockets, far above the melting point of most materials, but normal airbreathing jet engines use rather lower temperatures.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Cooling systems are employed to keep the temperature of the solid parts below the failure temperature.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Gas turbines have a secondary air system which is fundamental to the operation of the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It provides cooling air to the turbines, airflow into bearing cavities to prevent oil flowing out and cavity pressurization to ensure rotor thrust loads give acceptable thrust bearing life.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Air, bled from the compressor exit, passes around the combustor and is injected into the rim of the rotating turbine disc.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The cooling air then passes through complex passages within the turbine blades.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] After removing heat from the blade material, the air (now fairly hot) is vented, via cooling holes, into the main gas stream.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Cooling air for the turbine vanes undergoes a similar process.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Cooling the leading edge of the blade can be difficult, because the pressure of the cooling air just inside the cooling hole may not be much different from that of the oncoming gas stream.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] One solution is to incorporate a cover plate on the disc.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This acts as a centrifugal compressor to pressurize the cooling air before it enters the blade.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Another solution is to use an ultra-efficient turbine rim seal to pressurize the area where the cooling air passes across to the rotating disc.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Seals are used to prevent oil leakage, control air for cooling and prevent stray air flows into turbine cavities.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A series of (e.g. labyrinth) seals allow a small flow of bleed air to wash the turbine disc to extract heat and, at the same time, pressurize the turbine rim seal, to prevent hot gases entering the inner part of the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Other types of seals are hydraulic, brush, carbon etc.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Small quantities of compressor bleed air are also used to cool the shaft, turbine shrouds, etc.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Some air is also used to keep the temperature of the combustion chamber walls below critical.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This is done using primary and secondary airholes which allow a thin layer of air to cover the inner walls of the chamber preventing excessive heating.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Exit temperature is dependent on the turbine upper temperature limit depending on the material.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Reducing the temperature will also prevent thermal fatigue and hence failure.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Accessories may also need their own cooling systems using air from the compressor or outside air.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Air from compressor stages is also used for heating of the fan, airframe anti-icing and for cabin heat.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Which stage is bled from depends on the atmospheric conditions at that altitude.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Jet engines are controlled using Full Authority Digital Electronics Control systems.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Engine thrust has to be maintained or varied at the will of the pilot by varying the fuel flow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] But it has to be done without exceeding any limitations which could damage the engine or cause a flame-out (a combustible mixture has to be maintained in the combustion chambers to prevent lean or rich flame-out).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Complex hydromechanical units were used to implement these requirements before electronic engine controls were developed.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Usually there are two igniter plugs in different positions in the combustion system.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A high voltage spark is used to ignite the gases.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The voltage is stored up from a low voltage (usually 28 V DC) supply provided by the aircraft batteries.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It builds up to the right value in the ignition exciters (similar to automotive ignition coils) and is then released as a high energy spark.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Depending on various conditions, such as flying through heavy rainfall, the igniter continues to provide sparks to prevent combustion from failing if the flame inside goes out.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Of course, in the event that the flame does go out, there must be provision to relight.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] There is a limit of altitude and air speed at which an engine can obtain a satisfactory relight.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For example, the General Electric F404-400 uses one igniter for the combustor and one for the afterburner; the ignition system for the A/B incorporates an ultraviolet flame sensor to de-activate the igniter after light-off on minimum fuel has been detected.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Most modern ignition systems provide enough energy (20–40 kV) to be a lethal hazard should a person be in contact with the electrical lead when the system is activated, so team communication is vital when working on these systems.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Oil is used to lubricate and cool bearings and gears, to cool the inside surfaces of hot bearing compartments and to keep the system clean by passing the oil through filters.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It is also used as the squeeze-film in the main bearings.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Oil is lost from the system as a mist from the overboard vent (breather), and as drips from leaking seals on accessory drive shafts.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A (pressure) pump forces the oil through all the tubes going to the bearings and gears.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It shoots out of small holes (jets) pointing at them in their sealed enclosures (chambers or sumps).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The oil lubricates and cools them and becomes hot in turn.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It also finds its way into the small gap around the outside of the bearing where it gets squeezed when the bearing tries to move radially.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This oil film reduces (damps) the severity with which the supported shaft (with any out-of-balance) shakes the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Oil mist swirling around the bearing 'sees' very narrow escape paths round the shaft where it comes through the sump walls, but it's mostly held back by inrushing (sealing) air.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The oil drains from the sump and passes by a magnet (the chip detector) which attracts any magnetic debris.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It is pumped along, together with the air which sealed it in the sump, by (scavenge) pumps, then through a filter which traps any debris that may be present.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The hot oil is cooled by passing it through tubes with cold fuel on the other side (fuel/oil heat exchanger).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] If the oil is still too hot it passes through tubes with cold air on the other side (air/oil heat exchanger) in the bypass duct.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The sealing air has to be discarded, but with as little oil mist as possible.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Most of the oil is spun out of the air (centrifuged) and goes back in the tank.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The air escapes from the engine through a vent (breather).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Oil that escapes from the breather is a contributor to the engine oil consumption.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Breather vents are located on the gearbox on Rolls-Royce and Pratt & Whitney engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Breather air uses the hollow fan shaft on CFM engines.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] It passes through a flame arrestor before leaving the engine at the tip of the exhaust cone.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Oil leaks from accessory drive shaft seals are another contributor to oil consumption.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] An example maximum allowed is 3 drops per minute from carbon seals.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] One of the bearing sumps also includes the gears (so sometimes called the internal gearbox) which take power from the spool for driving an accessory gearbox on the outside of the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The power take-off for the accessory drive is a bevel gear specifically located next to the shaft thrust (ball) bearing to minimize unwanted movement relative to its mating radial driveshaft bevel gear.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This sump may include the thrust bearings for all shafts as well as the radial accessory drive.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For example, 3 ball bearings on the 3-shaft Rolls-Royce Trent engine which uses the IP shaft for the external gearbox, and 2 ball bearings on the 2-shaft CFM International LEAP engine with accessory drive from the HP shaft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The air intake (inlet U.S.) is an aerodynamic duct extending from an entry lip to the engine fan/compressor.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For supersonic intakes with variable geometry it is called an intake system, referring to the need for shock-wave and internal duct flow management using variable position surfaces (ramps or cones) and bypass doors.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The duct may be part of the fuselage structure with entry lip in various locations (aircraft nose - Corsair A-7, fuselage side - Dassault Mirage III), or located in an engine nacelle attached to the fuselage (Grumman F-14 Tomcat, Bombardier CRJ) or wing (Boeing 737).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Pitot inlets are used for subsonic aircraft.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A pitot inlet is little more than a tube with an aerodynamic fairing around it.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] When an aircraft is not moving, and there is no wind, air approaches the intake from all directions: directly ahead, from the side, and from behind.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] At low airspeeds, the streamtube approaching the lip is larger in cross-section than the lip flow area, whereas at the intake design flight Mach number the two flow areas are equal.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] At high flight speeds the streamtube is smaller, with excess air spilling round the lip.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Radiusing of the lip prevents flow separation and compressor inlet distortion at low speeds during crosswind operation and take-off rotation.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Supersonic intakes exploit shock waves to decelerate the airflow to a subsonic condition at compressor entry.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Conical (3-dimensional) and oblique shock waves (2D) are angled rearwards, like the bow wave on a ship or boat, and radiate from a flow disturbance such as a cone or a ramp.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For a given inlet Mach number, they are weaker than the equivalent normal shock wave and, although the flow slows down, it remains supersonic throughout.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Conical and oblique shock waves turn the flow, which continues in the new direction, until another flow disturbance is encountered downstream.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Note: Comments made regarding 3 dimensional conical shock waves, generally also apply to 2D oblique shock waves.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A sharp-lipped version of the pitot intake, described above for subsonic applications, performs quite well at moderate supersonic flight speeds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A detached normal shock wave forms just ahead of the intake lip and 'shocks' the flow down to a subsonic velocity.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] However, as flight speed increases to higher Mach numbers, the shock wave becomes stronger, causing a larger percentage decrease in stagnation pressure (i.e. poorer pressure recovery).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] An early US supersonic fighter, the F-100 Super Sabre, used such an intake.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] They are also found on more modern combat aircraft designs such as the F-16 Fighting Falcon and the F/A-18 Hornet that operate primarily operate at subsonic and transonic speeds with transient supersonic dashes, and are thus chosen for their light weight and simplicity due to their fixed geometry.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] a) exploit a combination of conical shock wave/s and a normal shock wave to improve pressure recovery at high supersonic flight speeds.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Conical shock wave/s are used to reduce the supersonic Mach number at entry to the normal shock wave, thereby reducing the resultant overall shock losses.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] b) have a design shock-on-lip flight Mach number, where the conical/oblique shock wave/s intercept the cowl lip, thus enabling the streamtube capture area to equal the intake lip area.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] However, below the shock-on-lip flight Mach number, the shock wave angle/s are less oblique, causing the streamline approaching the lip to be deflected by the presence of the cone/ramp.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Consequently, the intake capture area is less than the intake lip area, which reduces the intake airflow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Depending on the airflow characteristics of the engine, it may be desirable to lower the ramp angle or move the cone rearwards to refocus the shockwaves onto the cowl lip to maximise intake airflow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] c) are designed to have a normal shock in the ducting downstream of intake lip, so that the flow at compressor/fan entry is always subsonic.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This intake is known as a mixed-compression inlet.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] However, two difficulties arise for these intakes: one occurs during engine throttling while the other occurs when the aircraft speed (or Mach) changes.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] If the engine is throttled back, there is a reduction in the corrected (or non-dimensional) airflow of the LP compressor/fan, but (at supersonic conditions) the corrected airflow at the intake lip remains constant, because it is determined by the flight Mach number and intake incidence/yaw.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This discontinuity is overcome by the normal shock moving to a lower cross-sectional area in the ducting, to decrease the Mach number at entry to the shockwave.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This weakens the shockwave, improving the overall intake pressure recovery.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] So, the absolute airflow stays constant, whilst the corrected airflow at compressor entry falls (because of a higher entry pressure).
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Excess intake airflow may also be dumped overboard or into the exhaust system, to prevent the conical/oblique shock waves being disturbed by the normal shock being forced too far forward by engine throttling.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The second difficulty occurs when the aircraft Mach number changes.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The airflow has to be the same at the intake lip, at the throat and at the engine.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This statement is a consequence the conservation of mass.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] However, the airflow is not generally the same when the aircraft's supersonic speed changes.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This difficulty is known as the airflow matching problem which is solved by more complicated inlet designs than are typical of subsonic inlets.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For example, to match airflow, a supersonic inlet throat can be made variable and some air can be bypassed around the engine and then pumped as secondary air by an ejector nozzle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] If the inlet flow is not match, it may become unstable with the normal shock wave in the throat suddenly moving forward beyond the lip, known as inlet unstart.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Spillage drag is high and pressure recovery low with only a plane shock wave in place of the normal set of oblique shock waves.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] In the SR-71 installation the engine would continue to run although afterburner blowout sometimes occurred.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A Ferri-type intake, which used a prominent, swept-forward lip, a configuration also used for the wing-root inlets.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Notable aircraft that used this example was the Republic AP-75, XF-103, F-105, XF8U-3, and SSM-N-9 Regulus II cruise missile.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Many second generation supersonic fighter aircraft featured an inlet cone, which was used to form the conical shock wave.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This type of inlet cone is clearly seen at the very front of the English Electric Lightning and MiG-21 aircraft, for example.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The same approach can be used for air intakes mounted at the side of the fuselage, where a half cone serves the same purpose with a semicircular air intake, as seen on the F-104 Starfighter and BAC TSR-2.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Some intakes are biconic; that is they feature two conical surfaces: the first cone is supplemented by a second, less oblique, conical surface, which generates an extra conical shockwave, radiating from the junction between the two cones.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A biconic intake is usually more efficient than the equivalent conical intake, because the entry Mach number to the normal shock is reduced by the presence of the second conical shock wave.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The intake on the SR-71 had a translating conical spike which controlled the shock wave positions to give maximum pressure recovery.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] For rectangular intakes the equivalent way to generate the required shock system, compared to circular intake conical bodies, is to use ramps.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] A ramp causes an abrupt airflow deviation in supersonic flow as does the presence of a conical surface.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Two vertical ramps were used in the F-4 Phantom intake, the first with a fixed wedge angle of 10 degrees and the second with a variable additional deflection above Mach 1.2.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Horizontal ramps were used in the Concorde intakes.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] Some designs have variable capture area, such as on the F-15 Eagle.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] More modern "caret" style inlets, such as on the F-22 Raptor, have fixed ramps and cowls that are swept in multiple axes to generate oblique shocks, with shock positions adjusted using downstream pressure.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The fixed-geometry improves the aircraft's stealth characteristics and survivability.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] This enables the elimination of bleed and bypass systems, thus saving weight and cost.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] The DSI can be used to replace conventional methods of controlling supersonic and boundary layer airflow.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] At speeds up to Mach 2, the DSI achieves relatively decent pressure recovery performance and can be used to replace the intake ramp and inlet cone, which are more complex, heavy and expensive.
[src:components-of-jet-engines/components-of-jet-engines] They function by negative pressure, essentially "blowing" air in when the engine demands more than available airspeed can provide, then closing as speed increases.
